  <p>Ask brief, clear questions that users can understand.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Closed questions are easier than open ones.</li>
    <li>Several short questions are easier than 1 long one.</li>
  </ul>
  <p>Is there any way users could misunderstand the question?</p>
  <p>Ask questions that users can answer easily - from their heads or from information they have to hand.</p>
  <p>It may help to start with easy questions and to save more sensitive questions for later.</p>
  <p>Use familiar words in familiar ways, words like “poo” not “stool” - users’ words, not the organisation’s. Listen in on calls to the organisation’s call centre to get an idea of the words people use. For example, your service might want to know if the user has “hypertension”, while patients talk about “blood pressure” (meaning “high blood pressure”).</p>
  <p>Do not hide behind the passive tense. Not “Your GP will be notified” but “We will let your GP know.”<p>
  <p>Let users say "I'm not sure" or "I don't know", if these are valid answers.</p>
  <p>Use questions or statements consistently to help users get into a rhythm of answering. This lets them focus on the content of the questions rather than how they’re presented.</p>
  <p>It's OK to ask a follow up question. For example: “We think you mean this. Is that right?”</p>
  <p>Offer help: on the web, on phone or in person.</p>
  <p></p>


Do not ask 2 questions in 1, for example: “How often and how much time do you exercise each week?”

